<div class='communityQuestionSubTitle'>
Popular Answered Questions
</div>
<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/337100-is-the-narrator-a-nun-i-ask-because-in">Is the narrator a nun? I ask because in the introduction to the book she is called Miss Amy Leatheran, but Poirot repeatedly calls her &quot;‘ma soeur&quot; which I believe is French for Sister. Also, the letter she writes to her friend at the beginning of the book is addressed to Sister Curshaw.</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_337100'><a id="like_count_community_question_337100" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/337100?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">5 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F16360.Murder_in_Mesopotamia">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/337100-is-the-narrator-a-nun-i-ask-because-in">7 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/337100-is-the-narrator-a-nun-i-ask-because-in">See all 3 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1406361683i/20738920._UX100_CR0,18,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all">Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Sister was and still is the title given to the UK/NZ/Australian equivalent of a fully trained Registered Nurse (RN). The title &quot;Nurse&quot; is given to the<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Sister was and still is the title given to the UK/NZ/Australian equivalent of a fully trained Registered Nurse (RN). The title "Nurse" is given to the equivalent of a Licensed Practical Nurse (LPN) which I am told no longer exists in parts of the US.<br /><br />The title has its roots in the Anglican nursing communities of the 19th century. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
