<div id="review_2112302685" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2112302685" />
    <a title="Simona B" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5312173-simona-b"><img alt="Simona B" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408893128p2/5312173.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2112302685?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Simona B" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Simona B" href="/user/show/5312173-simona-b">Simona B</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5312173-simona-b?shelf=1900">1900</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5312173-simona-b?shelf=mystery-and-crime">mystery-and-crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5312173-simona-b?shelf=in-italian">in-italian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2112302685" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15410590368592803389"><b>“In the name of Allah, the Merciful, the Compassionate…”</b><br/><br/>Wonderful, absolutely wonderful. Nurse Leatheran, the narrator, is probably a little dull at times, even though it&apos;s clear she possesses a delightfully quick intelligence, and that&apos;s why <i>Murder in Mesopotamia</i> is not a five-star read for me. But the crime and the solution are <b>absolutely wonderful</b>, full of passions, obsessions, schemes... <b>one of the most</b> surprising and <b><i>human</i> mysteries</b> I have ever had the pleasure of reading. <br/><br/><br/><b>PS </b>not concerning</span>
  <span id="freeText15410590368592803389" style="display:none"><b>“In the name of Allah, the Merciful, the Compassionate…”</b><br /><br />Wonderful, absolutely wonderful. Nurse Leatheran, the narrator, is probably a little dull at times, even though it's clear she possesses a delightfully quick intelligence, and that's why <i>Murder in Mesopotamia</i> is not a five-star read for me. But the crime and the solution are <b>absolutely wonderful</b>, full of passions, obsessions, schemes... <b>one of the most</b> surprising and <b><i>human</i> mysteries</b> I have ever had the pleasure of reading. <br /><br /><br /><b>PS </b>not concerning the story itself: the suggested reading order issued by agathachristie.com (you can find it <a href="http://s3.amazonaws.com/agatha-christie-cms-production/Poirot-Reading-List.pdf" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a>) recommends that you read <i>Murder on the Orient Express</i> <u>before</u> <i>Murder in Mesopotamia</i>. Having read the <i>Orient Express</i> years ago, I was curious to find out the reason of such recommendation, and was surprised to find out that in truth it should say the opposite: at the end of <i>Murder in Mesopotamia</i>, indeed, we read that “M. Poirot went back to Syria and about a week later he went home on the Orient Express and got himself mixed up in another murder.” Therefore, <b>if you want to read Poirot's adventures somewhat in order</b>, my uncalled-for advice is to follow the one you can find <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hercule_Poirot_in_literature" rel="nofollow noopener">on this Wikipedia page</a> under “Books in chronological order.” I hope I helped. Happy reading!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15410590368592803389" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


