<span id="freeTextContainer17915765402952367729">Repeat read started on 17 April 2021. Again audio... but not BBC....<br/><br/>My 3rd or possibly 4th time with this . I see many racial prejudices now thwt I never saw in my earlier reads. Am I more sensitized or perhaps I am more intolerant? I can&apos;t decide.<br/>Nevertheless a clever story. <br/><br/><br/><br/>I loved the premise- have always been fascinated by the Orient, the archaeological dig and the languid way of life of Archaeologists family members who accompany them on the dig. So enjoyed this book more for the setting th</span>
  <span id="freeText17915765402952367729" style="display:none">Repeat read started on 17 April 2021. Again audio... but not BBC....<br /><br />My 3rd or possibly 4th time with this . I see many racial prejudices now thwt I never saw in my earlier reads. Am I more sensitized or perhaps I am more intolerant? I can't decide.<br />Nevertheless a clever story. <br /><br /><br /><br />I loved the premise- have always been fascinated by the Orient, the archaeological dig and the languid way of life of Archaeologists family members who accompany them on the dig. So enjoyed this book more for the setting than for the murder mystery.<br />The murder mystery rates only a 3 star, and it was the usual Christie offering - blackmail, hysterical females, calm collected females, questionable locals, masquerades and a highly improbable solution to a seemingly baffling crime.<br />Enjoyed the BBC audio with its various sound effects and the occasional background music which was pleasing to the ears, though it reminded me more of India than of Turkey or Mesopotamia.<br />Poirot, as usual, solved the case with a panache.</span>
